### Mathematical Foundations of Perpetual Futures Pricing: Derivations, Assumptions, and Implications from Ackerer, Hugonnier, and Jermann (2024/2025)\
\
Perpetual futures, as innovative derivative contracts without expiration, represent a significant advancement in financial markets, particularly in cryptocurrency and forex trading where they facilitate continuous leveraged exposure. The seminal work by Ackerer, Hugonnier, and Jermann (2024, NBER Working Paper 32936; published 2025 in *Mathematical Finance*) provides a rigorous no-arbitrage pricing framework, deriving closed-form solutions for linear, inverse, and quanto perpetuals in both discrete and continuous time. This analysis explores the models' mathematical structure, step-by-step derivations, and key insights, emphasizing conditions for spot-price convergence without an explicit interest component (\uc0\u953 =0). Such features hold profound implications for financial engineering, including potential Shariah-compliant designs by eliminating predetermined excess returns (riba), while addressing uncertainty (gharar) through convergence guarantees and speculation (maisir) via utility-focused applications.\
\
The models operate under a no-arbitrage paradigm with two currencies (a for domestic, b for foreign), spot exchange rate x_t (units of b per unit of a), and risk-free rates r_a, r_b. Funding comprises a premium term \uc0\u954 _t (intensity anchoring futures f_t to spot) and an optional interest-like term \u953 _t. No-bubble and integrability assumptions prevent divergences, ensuring finite prices in infinite horizons. The paper merges prior independent works, with extensions to everlasting options, and has been cited for its explicit formulas enabling empirical applications.\
\
#### Discrete-Time Models: Recursive Pricing and Convergence\
In discrete time, the framework assumes costless entry/exit and martingale properties under risk-neutral measures Q_a (for linear, margined in a) and Q_b (for inverse, margined in b).\
\
For **linear perpetual futures**, cash flows for a long position at t+1 are (f_\{t+1\} - f_t) - \uc0\u954 _t (f_t - x_t) - \u953 _t x_t. The no-arbitrage condition yields the recursion:\
\\[\
f_t = \\frac\{1\}\{1 + \\kappa_t\} \\mathbb\{E\}_\{Q_a\}^t [f_\{t+1\}] + \\frac\{\\kappa_t - \\iota_t\}\{1 + \\kappa_t\} x_t\
\\]\
Under integrability (\uc0\u8721  | (\u954 _\u963  - \u953 _\u963 ) x_\u963  | < \u8734 ) and no-bubble (lim E [discounted f_T] = 0), iterating forward gives Theorem 1:\
\\[\
f_t = \\mathbb\{E\}_\{Q_a\}^t \\left[ \\sum_\{\\sigma=t\}^\{\\infty\} \\left( \\prod_\{\\tau=t\}^\{\\sigma-1\} \\frac\{1\}\{1 + \\kappa_\\tau\} \\right) (\\kappa_\\sigma - \\iota_\\sigma) x_\\sigma \\right]\
\\]\
To derive: Substitute recursively, apply dominated convergence for the limit. For \uc0\u953 =0 and -1 < \u954 _t, a random time \u952 _t (geometric with parameter \u954 _t / (1 + \u954 _t)) represents:\
\\[\
f_t = \\mathbb\{E\}_\{Q_a\}^t [x_\{\\theta_t\}]\
\\]\
Proof: Match probabilities to the iterated weights, ensuring the expectation replicates the sum.\
\
With constants and (1 + r_a) / ((1 + \uc0\u954 )(1 + r_b)) < 1, Proposition 1 gives:\
\\[\
f_t = \\frac\{(\\kappa - \\iota)(1 + r_b)\}\{r_b - r_a + \\kappa (1 + r_b)\} x_t\
\\]\
Derivation: Assume affine f_t = \uc0\u946  x_t, plug into recursion with spot dynamics E[x_\{t+1\}] = (1 + r_a) / (1 + r_b) x_t, solve for \u946 . Convergence without \u953  (\u953 =0) holds if r_a = r_b, yielding f_t = x_t (Corollary 1), replicable by borrowing in a and investing in b.\
\
**Inverse perpetuals** mirror this, quoted in a but margined in b (x^*_t = 1/x_t). Cash flows lead to Theorem 2 for 1/f_\{I,t\}, with explicit:\
\\[\
f_\{I,t\} = \\frac\{r_a - r_b + \\kappa_I (1 + r_a)\}\{\\kappa_I - \\iota_I\} x_t\
\\]\
(Proposition 2). Without \uc0\u953 _I=0 and r_a = r_b, f_\{I,t\} = x_t (Corollary 2).\
\
#### Continuous-Time Models: Stochastic Differentials and Integrals\
Transitioning to continuous time, dynamics are df_t = [\uc0\u953 _t x_t + \u954 _t (f_t - x_t)] dt + dM_t (M martingale under Q_a). Theorem 3:\
\\[\
f_t = \\mathbb\{E\}_\{Q_a\}^t \\left[ \\int_t^\\infty e^\{-\\int_t^s \\kappa_u du\} (\\kappa_s - \\iota_s) x_s ds \\right]\
\\]\
Derivation: Discounted process is martingale by Ito; integrate under no-bubble (lim E [e^\{-\uc0\u8747  \u954 \} f_T] =0) and integrability. For \u953 =0, exponential time \u964  ~ Exp(\u8747  \u954  du) gives f_t = E [x_\{t+\u964 \}].\
\
Constants yield Proposition 3:\
\\[\
f_t = \\frac\{\\kappa - \\iota\}\{\\kappa + r_b - r_a\} x_t\
\\]\
(if denominator >0). Without \uc0\u953 =0 and r_a = r_b, f_t = x_t (Corollary 3). Proof: Solve ODE from dynamics.\
\
**Inverse** (Theorem 4) and **quanto** (Theorem 5, for third currency c) follow similarly, with Black-Scholes quanto (Proposition 5) incorporating correlations:\
\\[\
f_\{Q,t\} = \\frac\{\\kappa - \\iota\}\{r_c - \\sigma_x \\sigma_z - r_a + \\kappa\} z_t\
\\]\
Derivation: Log-normal SDEs, characteristic functions for expectations.\
\
#### Everlasting Options: Extensions Beyond Futures\
Theorem 6 generalizes to payoffs \uc0\u966 (x_t):\
\\[\
f_\{o,t\} = \\mathbb\{E\}_\{Q_a\}^t \\left[ \\int_t^\\infty e^\{-\\int_t^s \\kappa_\{o,u\} du\} \\kappa_\{o,s\} \\phi(x_s) ds \\right] = \\mathbb\{E\}_\{Q_a\}^t [\\phi(x_\{\\theta_\{o,t\}\})]\
\\]\
Black-Scholes calls/puts (Proposition 6) use power solutions to PDEs, with roots \uc0\u928  <0, \u920  >1 solving quadratics.\
\
