### Implications for Shariah-Compliant Options\
The everlasting options framework in Ackerer et al. (2024) introduces perpetual payoffs without expiry, priced via integrals or random times. For Islamic finance, this means potential riba avoidance: setting \uc0\u953 =0 ensures funding depends solely on premiums (\u954 ), mirroring profit-sharing over fixed excess. However, options face scrutiny\'97Zulkarnain & Syibly (2024) deem derivatives haram for gharar (uncertainty in outcomes) and maisir (zero-sum bets). Progressive alternatives like arbun (down-payment options) or wa'ad (promises) could adapt everlasting models for hedging, e.g., RWAs, but prohibitions persist without physical delivery (qabdh). Uluyol (2024) suggests incorporating Black-Scholes into Shariah tools, enabling compliant pricing if speculation is minimized.\
