### Shariah-Compliant Perpetual Options: Integrating Mathematical Pricing Models with Islamic Jurisprudence\
\
Perpetual or everlasting options, as perpetual derivatives without expiration, represent a frontier in financial engineering that intersects with Islamic finance's stringent prohibitions on riba (usury), gharar (excessive uncertainty), and maisir (gambling-like speculation). Drawing from Ackerer, Hugonnier, and Jermann's (2024) no-arbitrage framework\'97merged from prior works and published in *Mathematical Finance* (2025)\'97this analysis explores implications for Shariah compliance, deriving key proofs step-by-step while synthesizing fiqh perspectives. The models' ability to achieve convergence without explicit interest (\uc0\u953 =0) offers proactive reforms, potentially enabling riba-free hedging, though conservative fatwas emphasize inherent risks. This superset expands the direct answer, incorporating document insights: Ahmed's (2026) DEX reforms for premium-only funding, Zulkarnain & Syibly's (2024) CEX critiques, Glatzel & Nagel's (2024) unrelated probabilistics, and community X discussions on speculation.\
\
#### Core Mathematical Insights and Shariah Relevance\
Ackerer et al. assume no-arbitrage with measures Q_a/Q_b, rates r_a/r_b, and funding \uc0\u954 _t/\u953 _t. Everlasting options extend perpetual futures, pricing payoffs \u966 (x_t) via integrals or random times. For Shariah, \u953 =0 avoids riba as predetermined excess (El-Gamal, 2006), relying on \u954  for market-driven anchoring\'97aligning with profit-sharing (mudarabah). However, options' optional exercise introduces gharar (uncertain outcomes) and maisir (speculative bets), per AAOIFI Standard 57 (2022) prohibiting derivatives. Progressive views (Uluyol, 2024) permit if utility-focused, e.g., hedging RWAs without leverage excess. Zulkarnain & Syibly critique Binance for uncertain rates harming parties, but DEX everlasting options could mitigate via on-chain transparency. X posts (@degenjurist, 2026) advocate wa'ad-based guarantees, while @maiinas (2026) rejects leverage as riba/maisir. ResearchGate preprint (2026) supports DEX if gharar minimized, tying to Ackerer's convergence for stability.\
